post_text:
Starting Tuesday, September 8, 2020, we are excited to announce that free school meals, both breakfast and lunch, will be available for ALL students. Students may receive one FREE school breakfast and one FREE school lunch each day school is in session.

All Hybrid students when attending school will receive a free breakfast and a free lunch at school and may choose to take home a free breakfast and lunch for their remote instruction days not at school.

Remote students not attending school will be able to continue to pick up bundled free meals two times a week. These meals will not need to be preordered. Meal pick-up locations will continue at Jackson, Curtin, Lycomng Valley and WAMS. More information will be posted on district website and Facebook page.

This is a result of federal funds made available nationally and will remain in effect until December 31, 2020 or until funding runs out.

post_text:
What is WASD Hybrid Learning?

Hybrid learning is a combination of in-person and remote online learning. The in-person time happens in class where students have direct access to their teacher. The remote online learning time, with the same teacher, can be done at home or other remote location.

To gather more information on Hybrid Learning as well as the Hybrid Day Schedule click the following link: https://www.wasd.org/our-district/wasd-hybrid-phase-information

JOIN OUR TEAM: We're hiring for the 2020-21 school year! We're looking to fill a school psychologist position, as well as our executive director of the #WASD education foundation and public relations position. To learn more about these positions, or to apply, see below:

- Executive Director of the WASD Education Foundation & Public Relations: Responsible for fundraising, coordinating projects, and maintaining appropriate records for the Foundation. This position is also responsible for developing a planned and systematic process of communication between the school district and internal and external stakeholders. This position is responsible for developing all press releases and other news/district publications. https://bit.ly/2N2Gge3

- School Psychologist: Provides assessments and consultations related to the abilities, aptitude, interests, achievements, personality, and adjustment of individual students who exhibit learning and/or emotional problems. https://bit.ly/2Abd1T9

post_text:
Well, it was different, but we did it. If nothing else, tonight's graduation truly ‚Äî and to some degree literally ‚Äî exemplified its theme based on a quote by Vivian Greene: "Life isn't about waiting for the storm to pass ... it's about learning to dance in the rain."

Congratulations to the Williamsport Area High School #Classof2020! While the style of your sendoff wasn't anything we would've planned otherwise, it was great to see you all again. Best wishes to you, good luck, and thank you for making us feel #MillionaireProud tonight.

(Please note that a commemorative video of tonight's ceremony will be produced and released on or by next Friday, June 12, along with a release of the pre-recorded speeches that would've been heard tonight.)

shared_text:
Williamsport Area High School Track and Field
May 16 at 8:47 AM ¬∑

Williamsport‚Äôs legendary coach Sam Belle has recently been battling some health concerns. As all of you know, Sam lives for the moments he spends with the track and field athletes every spring. With the 2020 season being cancelled, Sam does not have the opportunity to enjoy his favorite pastime. We want to show him our support and give him the same encouragement that he has provided to all the Millionaires over the years.

Join us on Thursday, May 21st for a drive-by parade. We will assemble at the Pajama Factory at 3pm and proceed down Cemetery street in front of Coach Belle‚Äôs house. Prepare your signs and gather some noise makers as we applaud his courageous battle with lots of Millionaire Pride!
We ask that you please stay in your vehicle in order to ensure everyone's safety.
üî¥‚ö™üé©

The College Board
March 20 at 1:24 PM ¬∑

We know the coronavirus has created challenges for AP students and teachers. Here‚Äôs how the College Board will support you during this time:

1Ô∏è‚É£ We‚Äôre providing free, live and on-demand AP courses

To support AP students affected by school closures due to COVID-19, students and schools will have access to live AP review lessons, delivered by AP teachers from across the country. Lessons will begin March 25.

2Ô∏è‚É£ We‚Äôre developing a new at-home testing option

Because of the challenges created by COVID-19, we‚Äôre developing a new at-home AP Exam option. Students will be able to test on a computer, tablet, or smartphone.

We will invest so that every AP student impacted by COVID-19 has the tools and connectivity they need to review AP content online and take the exam from home.

During this challenging time, we will work to give every AP student the opportunity to earn the college credit and placement they‚Äôve been working toward all year while maintaining a focus on the health and safety of our AP community.

More details here: http://spr.ly/61851tbn3.

UPDATE: We all know this is a difficult and stressful time for all adults across the country, but it is also important that we address the social and emotional needs of our children. Many children struggle to understand what is going on currently with the coronavirus pandemic and why they cannot go to school or play with their friends. As a district, we believe that it was important to share with you some resources that may assist you in talking to your child about the COVID-19 and to help you assist with their stress during this situation. Included at the in our resource listing are some local resources should your child have significant mental or emotional needs.

The most important thing we can do right now on a daily basis is to reinforce to children that they are safe, not to be afraid, to answer their questions and try to keep them in some sort of routine at home.

The resources provided at the link below have been made accessible from our website and have been reviewed by our counselors and social workers.

‚ÑπÔ∏è https://bit.ly/398INMu

The last week has kept our attention focused on COVID-19 mitigation planning, but we haven't forgotten about some of our students' recent successes that we still want to share with you.

Our #WAHS Future Business Leaders of America (#FBLA) students recently attended the Pennsylvania Council on Financial Literacy Entrepreneurship Challenge Workshop at Susquehanna University. The students worked with local business professionals and professors from SU to collaborate on the development of a unique, viable business idea and draft a business plan. From there, students presented the plan to a panel of judges via an ‚Äúelevator speech‚Äù for an opportunity to win a team prize ‚Äî and we did!

The winning idea was their ‚ÄúJack of All Trades‚Äù app, which earned the team a $100 prize to share. From left is Michael Cendoma, Isabelle Brumbaugh, Christopher Martin, Dillan Read and FBLA Adviser Marianne Miller.

#MillionaireProud

SCHOOL CLOSURE UPDATE: Limited school personnel will be available at each WASD school tomorrow Monday, March 16, from 8 a.m. to 3 p.m. for parents and/or guardians to retrieve student medication and any critical items that may be needed while schools are closed.

It is imperative that parents/guardians retrieve these items tomorrow. It will not be possible to pick up any items beyond tomorrow until schools re-open, as staff will not be working. Critical items include only phones/electronic devices/coats. Other non-critical student items will be secured in schools until students return.

Information on the planned meal distribution to students will be shared shortly with families on our website and social media channels.

To view updates and previous communication on this evolving situation, visit our dedicated webpage here: http://bit.ly/2IT6zS5

Meet Mr. O, an AmeriCorps volunteer, and first-grader Kenyon, both from Stevens Primary School. The two deepened their bond recently when Mr. O reacted "on instinct," he says, to perform the Heimlich maneuver on Kenyon after he spotted him choking on his lunch in the cafeteria. We want to thank Mr. O for his vigilance and springing into action to help save Kenyon!

Watch for a full story on Mr. O's heroic move in an upcoming edition of the Williamsport Sun-Gazette.

"Life's most persistent and urgent question is, 'What are you doing for others?' "

Keeping Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s quote in mind and recognizing that "a day off should be a day on," third-grade students in Mrs. Holt's classroom at Cochran Primary School made "Snowmen for Seniors" out of styrofoam cups. The decorated cups included a hot cocoa mix to help keep some residents of The Williamsport Home warm during these cold winter days.

ONE IN A MILLION: On the theme of "You Are One in a Million(aire)," Williamsport Area High School kicked off Mental Health Awareness Week with an exercise in self expression to "promote the idea that each student is special and contributes to our school in a positive way," according to school psychologist Keri Nasdeo and social worker Heather Way.

At lunch, students were encouraged to write on a card what makes them 1/1,000,000 at a display table that also contained a spread of resources from places like NAMI of North Central Pennsylvania and the West Branch Drug and Alcohol Abuse Commission.
